{"title_page": "Mike Mattison", "text_new": "{{Short description|American musician and vocalist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Mike Mattison\n| image            = Mike Mattison.jpg\n| caption          = Mattison fronting Scrapomatic, opening for the [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]]\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota\n| birth_place      = \n| birth_date       = December 14, 1969\n| death_date       = \n| instrument       = Vocals, piano, [[clarinet]], [[tenor saxophone]] [[french horn]], [[trombone]], [[upright bass]]\n| genre            = [[Blues]], [[blues rock]], soul, [[world music]], [[R&B]], [[jazz fusion]]\n| occupation       = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active     = \n| label            = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[Alligator Records|Alligator]], Landslide Records\n| associated_acts  = [[The Derek Trucks Band]], [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]], [[Scrapomatic]], [[Susan Tedeschi]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Mike Mattison''' is an American musician and vocalist<ref name=\"Gritz1\">{{cite web|url=http://swampland.com/articles/view/title:mike_mattison_the_gritz_interview|title=Mike Mattison: The Gritz Interview|last=Halsey|first=Derek|date=1998\u20132009|work=Gritz interview|publisher=Swampland Inc|accessdate=August 1, 2010}}</ref> of the [[Grammy Award]]-winning blues rock/soul group, the [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]], as well as lead vocalist and co-founder of the [[blues rock]] trio [[Scrapomatic]]. Mattison's vocal sound has been described as \"strong,\" with an \"expressive blues voice\".<ref name=\"Jazztimes\">{{cite web|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/17691-td-toronto-jazz-festival|title=TD Toronto Jazz Festival|last=Conrad|first=Thomas|date=1989\u20132010|work=Tanglewood Jazz Festival|publisher=Jazz Times|accessdate=August 27, 2010}}</ref> As lead vocalist of Scrapomatic, he picked up a nomination for [[Minnesota Music Academy|Minnesota Music Awards]] best male vocalist, and both he and co-founder [[Paul Olsen (musician)|Paul Olsen]] were also nominated for best [[R&B]] Group.<ref name=\"last.fm1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Scrapomatic/+wiki|title=Scrapomatic Biography|date=November 21, 2008|work=last.fm|publisher=CBS Interactive Music Group|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> Mattison was previously the lead vocalist of the Grammy Award-winning [[Derek Trucks Band]] and has been a main songwriter of all three bands. He is also an active essayist who publishes on music and poetry. Since 2013 Mattison and Ernest Suarez have edited \u201cHot Rocks: Songs and Verse,\u201d an ongoing feature in Five Points: A Journal of Literature and Art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fivepoints.gsu.edu/issue/five-points-vol-15-3/ |title=Five Points, Vol. 15 No. 3 - Five Points - A Journal of Literature and Art|website=Fivepoints.gsu.edu|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>  He serves on the Council of the Association of Literary Critics, Scholars, and Writers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alscw.org/about/governance/council/|title= Council |website=Alscw.org|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMattison was born and grew to adulthood in [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota,<ref name=\"last.fm1\"/><ref name=\"funkydoryinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.funkyband.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=52|title=Mike Mattison (singer with the DTB) Interview|last=Fothergill|first=Jules|date=May 24, 2006|work=Northsyde|publisher=Funkydory|accessdate=August 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007210744/http://www.funkyband.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=52|archive-date=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> during a period where he was encouraged to learn and experiment with a variety of musical instruments, which appealed to him.  Before graduation from high school, he'd learned, with differing levels of accomplishment, to play the [[recorder (musical instrument)|recorder]], [[clarinet]], [[tenor saxophone]], [[french horn]], [[trombone]], [[Upright bass|bass]], and guitar, in addition to his natural ability to sing. He was influenced by [[jazz]], the [[Blues music|blues]], and [[Roots revival|roots music]].  Mattison began exploring songwriting and performing with a friend who had also been raised in Minneapolis, [[Paul Olsen (musician)|Paul Olsen]]. The pair met in 1993 at a [[Parliament-Funkadelic]] concert, and began playing [[R&B]] and [[Blues music|blues]]-based music together afterward.<ref name=\"the washingtonpost1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/07/AR2010010701376.html|title=Scrapomatic band fuses blues, pop into an eclectic sound on 'Sidewalk Caesars'|last=Suarez|first=Ernest|date=January 8, 2010|work=The Washington Post|publisher=Washington Post Company|accessdate=August 28, 2010}}</ref> Mattison's acceptance and subsequent college education at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] brought him east, and he convinced Olsen to move with him.\n\nMattison graduated from Harvard with a degree in English and American literature. Mattison and Olsen continued playing and performing together, forming the duo they named Scrapomatic. In 2002, [[Craig Street]] and John Snyder, the two record producers that had business ties with [[blues rock]] musician [[Derek Trucks]] independently suggested Mattison as the person to fill the newly vacated position of lead vocalist for The Derek Trucks Band.<ref name=\"npr 2006 worldcafe1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5664073&refresh=true|title=The Derek Trucks Band in Concert|year=2010|work=The World Cafe Live: NPR|publisher=NPR (National Public Radio)|accessdate=August 24, 2010}}</ref> Trucks, who was in New York City on business, had begun looking at the information and photos supplied of Mattison, and having seen Mattison's photos and demos singing, was surprised to find he was in the same subway car. After Trucks recognized him and introduced himself, Mattison performed in several concerts following the unusual meeting with [[The Derek Trucks Band]], and shortly afterward, landed the position, where he has remained since his entry into the band. He continues to maintain his position in Scrapomatic, with the duo frequently opening for The Derek Trucks Band.\n\nMike Mattison's voice has been considered a \"perfect fit\" for The Derek Trucks Band. After listening to the band play the arrangement of \"[[I Wish I Knew How It Would Feel to Be Free|I Wish I Knew]]\" in the style of [[Nina Simone]], an [[National Public Radio|NPR]] host mentioned a \"growly\" quality to Mattison's voice, which Trucks was able to closely duplicate on the [[slide guitar]]. The next song had a completely different sound altogether, a rendition of a song by [[Skip James]], where Mattison sang in a [[falsetto]].<ref name=\"NPR 6stringcreation 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5300263|title=Six-String Creation: The Derek Trucks Band|date=March 25, 2006|work=NPR Music Studio Stations|publisher=npr 2010|accessdate=September 20, 2010}}</ref> His wide range appealed to Trucks, who was looking for a lead vocalist that was not the usual fare. Within The Derek Trucks Band, Mattison's voice has been described as an instrument, rather than that of a focal point as frontman.<ref name=\"JaredNewman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jambase.com/Articles/7890/DEREK-TRUCKS-BAND-SLIDES-INTO-NYC|title=DEREK TRUCKS BAND SLIDES INTO NYC|last=Newman|first=Jared|date=1998\u20132010|publisher=JamBase Inc.|accessdate=September 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, The Derek Trucks Band announced a hiatus, and Mike Mattison joined the new group, [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]], as a backing vocalist and songwriter. One of his compositions, \"Midnight in Harlem,\" appears on the DVD release of Eric Clapton's [[Crossroads Guitar Festival]] 2010.\n\nOn July 17, 2013, Mike Mattison launched a Kickstarter Project,<ref name=\"Kickstarter Project 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/mikemattison/untitled-not-so-secret-mike-mattison-solo-album|title=(Untitled, Not-So-Secret) Mike Mattison Solo Album|website=Kickstarter.com|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref> called \"untitled-not-so-secret-mike-Mattison-solo-album\" which successfully raised its funding goal on August 17, 2013. The project will be used to finish recording, mixing and mastering of his new album, which was expected to arrive around October 2013.\n\nMike Mattison released his solo CD \"You Can't Fight Love\" on Landslide Records (LDCD-1042) with a street date of June 3, 2014. In addition to recording and touring with the Tedeschi Trucks Band and Scrapomatic, Mattison and Ernest Suarez have held seminars on a literary genre they call Poetic Song Verse at various universities since 2016.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===With Scrapomatic===\n* 2002 \u2013 ''Scrapomatic''\n* 2006 \u2013 ''Alligator Love Cry'' [[Alligator Records]]\n* 2008 \u2013 ''Sidewalk Caesars'' Landslide Records\n\n===With The Derek Trucks Band===\n* ''[[Live at Georgia Theatre]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Songlines (The Derek Trucks Band album)|Songlines]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Songlines Live]]'' (2006, DVD)\n* ''[[Already Free]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Roadsongs (The Derek Trucks Band album)|Roadsongs]]'' (2010)\n\n===With Tedeschi Trucks Band===\n* ''[[Revelator (Tedeschi Trucks Band album)|Revelator]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Everybody's Talkin' (Tedeschi Trucks Band album)|Everybody's Talkin']]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Made Up Mind]] (2013)\n* ''[[Let Me Get By]] (2016)\n* ''[[Live from the Fox Oakland]] (2017)\n* ''[[Signs (Tedeschi Trucks Band album)|Signs]] (2019) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tedeschitrucksband.com/news/signs|title=TTB's Fourth Studio Album SIGNS Is Available Now|website=Tedeschitrucjband.com|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Solo===\n* ''You Can't Fight Love'' Landslide Records (2014)\n*''Afterglow'' (Landslide Records, 2020)\n\n===Other contributions===\n* ''Soul Summit'' (2008) (Maysa, [[Susan Tedeschi]], and Mike Mattison)<ref name=\"SoulSummit1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-01-08/music/soul-summit/|title=Soul Summit; Here is the bland soul-karaoke record you did not request|last=Torres|first=Richard|date=August 1, 2008|newspaper=The Village Voice|pages=Pg.1|accessdate=August 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons}}\n{{The Derek Trucks Band}}\n{{Tedeschi Trucks Band}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mattison, Mike}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Blues rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:Contemporary blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:American blues singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Singers from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:The Derek Trucks Band members]]\n[[Category:Tedeschi Trucks Band members]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American musician and vocalist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name             = Mike Mattison\n| image            = Mike Mattison.jpg\n| caption          = Mattison fronting Scrapomatic, opening for the [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]]\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| origin           = [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota\n| birth_place      = \n| birth_date       = December 14, 1969\n| death_date       = \n| instrument       = Vocals, piano, [[clarinet]], [[tenor saxophone]] [[french horn]], [[trombone]], [[upright bass]]\n| genre            = [[Blues]], [[blues rock]], soul, [[world music]], [[R&B]], [[jazz fusion]]\n| occupation       = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active     = \n| label            = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]], [[Alligator Records|Alligator]], Landslide Records\n| associated_acts  = [[The Derek Trucks Band]], [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]], [[Scrapomatic]], [[Susan Tedeschi]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Mike Mattison''' is an American musician and vocalist<ref name=\"Gritz1\">{{cite web|url=http://swampland.com/articles/view/title:mike_mattison_the_gritz_interview|title=Mike Mattison: The Gritz Interview|last=Halsey|first=Derek|date=1998\u20132009|work=Gritz interview|publisher=Swampland Inc|accessdate=August 1, 2010}}</ref> of the [[Grammy Award]]-winning blues rock/soul group, the [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]], as well as lead vocalist and co-founder of the [[blues rock]] trio [[Scrapomatic]]. Mattison's vocal sound has been described as \"strong,\" with an \"expressive blues voice\".<ref name=\"Jazztimes\">{{cite web|url=http://jazztimes.com/articles/17691-td-toronto-jazz-festival|title=TD Toronto Jazz Festival|last=Conrad|first=Thomas|date=1989\u20132010|work=Tanglewood Jazz Festival|publisher=Jazz Times|accessdate=August 27, 2010}}</ref> As lead vocalist of Scrapomatic, he picked up a nomination for [[Minnesota Music Academy|Minnesota Music Awards]] best male vocalist, and both he and co-founder [[Paul Olsen (musician)|Paul Olsen]] were also nominated for best [[R&B]] Group.<ref name=\"last.fm1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Scrapomatic/+wiki|title=Scrapomatic Biography|date=November 21, 2008|work=last.fm|publisher=CBS Interactive Music Group|accessdate=August 3, 2010}}</ref> Mattison was previously the lead vocalist of the Grammy Award-winning [[Derek Trucks Band]] and has been a main songwriter of all three bands. He is also an active essayist who publishes on music and poetry. Since 2013 Mattison and Ernest Suarez have edited \u201cHot Rocks: Songs and Verse,\u201d an ongoing feature in Five Points: A Journal of Literature and Art.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fivepoints.gsu.edu/issue/five-points-vol-15-3/ |title=Five Points, Vol. 15 No. 3 - Five Points - A Journal of Literature and Art|website=Fivepoints.gsu.edu|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>  He serves on the Council of the Association of Literary Critics, Scholars, and Writers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://alscw.org/about/governance/council/|title= Council |website=Alscw.org|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nMattison was born and grew to adulthood in [[Minneapolis]], Minnesota,<ref name=\"last.fm1\"/><ref name=\"funkydoryinterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.funkyband.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=52|title=Mike Mattison (singer with the DTB) Interview|last=Fothergill|first=Jules|date=May 24, 2006|work=Northsyde|publisher=Funkydory|accessdate=August 3, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007210744/http://www.funkyband.com/forum/viewtopic.php?t=52|archive-date=October 7, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> during a period where he was encouraged to learn and experiment with a variety of musical instruments, which appealed to him.  Before graduation from high school, he'd learned, with differing levels of accomplishment, to play the [[recorder (musical instrument)|recorder]], [[clarinet]], [[tenor saxophone]], [[french horn]], [[trombone]], [[Upright bass|bass]], and guitar, in addition to his natural ability to sing. He was influenced by [[jazz]], the [[Blues music|blues]], and [[Roots revival|roots music]].  Mattison began exploring songwriting and performing with a friend who had also been raised in Minneapolis, [[Paul Olsen (musician)|Paul Olsen]]. The pair met in 1993 at a [[Parliament-Funkadelic]] concert, and began playing [[R&B]] and [[Blues music|blues]]-based music together afterward.<ref name=\"the washingtonpost1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/01/07/AR2010010701376.html|title=Scrapomatic band fuses blues, pop into an eclectic sound on 'Sidewalk Caesars'|last=Suarez|first=Ernest|date=January 8, 2010|work=The Washington Post|publisher=Washington Post Company|accessdate=August 28, 2010}}</ref> Mattison's acceptance and subsequent college education at [[Harvard University|Harvard]] brought him east, and he convinced Olsen to move with him.\n\nMattison graduated from Harvard with a degree in English and American literature. Mattison and Olsen continued playing and performing together, forming the duo they named Scrapomatic. In 2002, [[Craig Street]] and John Snyder, the two record producers that had business ties with [[blues rock]] musician [[Derek Trucks]] independently suggested Mattison as the person to fill the newly vacated position of lead vocalist for The Derek Trucks Band.<ref name=\"npr 2006 worldcafe1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5664073&refresh=true|title=The Derek Trucks Band in Concert|year=2010|work=The World Cafe Live: NPR|publisher=NPR (National Public Radio)|accessdate=August 24, 2010}}</ref> Trucks, who was in New York City on business, had begun looking at the information and photos supplied of Mattison, and having seen Mattison's photos and demos singing, was surprised to find he was in the same subway car. After Trucks recognized him and introduced himself, Mattison performed in several concerts following the unusual meeting with [[The Derek Trucks Band]], and shortly afterward, landed the position, where he has remained since his entry into the band. He continues to maintain his position in Scrapomatic, with the duo frequently opening for The Derek Trucks Band.\n\nMike Mattison's voice has been considered a \"perfect fit\" for The Derek Trucks Band. After listening to the band play the arrangement of \"[[I Wish I Knew How It Would Feel to Be Free|I Wish I Knew]]\" in the style of [[Nina Simone]], an [[National Public Radio|NPR]] host mentioned a \"growly\" quality to Mattison's voice, which Trucks was able to closely duplicate on the [[slide guitar]]. The next song had a completely different sound altogether, a rendition of a song by [[Skip James]], where Mattison sang in a [[falsetto]].<ref name=\"NPR 6stringcreation 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=5300263|title=Six-String Creation: The Derek Trucks Band|date=March 25, 2006|work=NPR Music Studio Stations|publisher=npr 2010|accessdate=September 20, 2010}}</ref> His wide range appealed to Trucks, who was looking for a lead vocalist that was not the usual fare. Within The Derek Trucks Band, Mattison's voice has been described as an instrument, rather than that of a focal point as frontman.<ref name=\"JaredNewman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jambase.com/Articles/7890/DEREK-TRUCKS-BAND-SLIDES-INTO-NYC|title=DEREK TRUCKS BAND SLIDES INTO NYC|last=Newman|first=Jared|date=1998\u20132010|publisher=JamBase Inc.|accessdate=September 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, The Derek Trucks Band announced a hiatus, and Mike Mattison joined the new group, [[Tedeschi Trucks Band]], as a backing vocalist and songwriter. One of his compositions, \"Midnight in Harlem,\" appears on the DVD release of Eric Clapton's [[Crossroads Guitar Festival]] 2010.\n\nOn July 17, 2013, Mike Mattison launched a Kickstarter Project,<ref name=\"Kickstarter Project 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/mikemattison/untitled-not-so-secret-mike-mattison-solo-album|title=(Untitled, Not-So-Secret) Mike Mattison Solo Album|website=Kickstarter.com|accessdate=2014-05-18}}</ref> called \"untitled-not-so-secret-mike-Mattison-solo-album\" which successfully raised its funding goal on August 17, 2013. The project will be used to finish recording, mixing and mastering of his new album, which was expected to arrive around October 2013.\n\nMike Mattison released his solo CD \"You Can't Fight Love\" on Landslide Records (LDCD-1042) with a street date of June 3, 2014. In addition to recording and touring with the Tedeschi Trucks Band and Scrapomatic, Mattison and Ernest Suarez have held seminars on a literary genre they call Poetic Song Verse at various universities since 2016.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===With Scrapomatic===\n* 2002 \u2013 ''Scrapomatic''\n* 2006 \u2013 ''Alligator Love Cry'' [[Alligator Records]]\n* 2008 \u2013 ''Sidewalk Caesars'' Landslide Records\n\n===With The Derek Trucks Band===\n* ''[[Live at Georgia Theatre]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Songlines (The Derek Trucks Band album)|Songlines]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Songlines Live]]'' (2006, DVD)\n* ''[[Already Free]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Roadsongs (The Derek Trucks Band album)|Roadsongs]]'' (2010)\n\n===With Tedeschi Trucks Band===\n* ''[[Revelator (Tedeschi Trucks Band album)|Revelator]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Everybody's Talkin' (Tedeschi Trucks Band album)|Everybody's Talkin']]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Made Up Mind]] (2013)\n* ''[[Let Me Get By]] (2016)\n* ''[[Live from the Fox Oakland]] (2017)\n* ''[[Signs (Tedeschi Trucks Band album)|Signs]] (2019) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tedeschitrucksband.com/news/signs|title=TTB's Fourth Studio Album SIGNS Is Available Now|website=Tedeschitrucjband.com|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Solo===\n* ''You Can't Fight Love'' Landslide Records (2014)\n* Afterglow (Landslide Records, 2020)\n\n===Other contributions===\n* ''Soul Summit'' (2008) (Maysa, [[Susan Tedeschi]], and Mike Mattison)<ref name=\"SoulSummit1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2008-01-08/music/soul-summit/|title=Soul Summit; Here is the bland soul-karaoke record you did not request|last=Torres|first=Richard|date=August 1, 2008|newspaper=The Village Voice|pages=Pg.1|accessdate=August 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons}}\n{{The Derek Trucks Band}}\n{{Tedeschi Trucks Band}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mattison, Mike}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Blues rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:African-American musicians]]\n[[Category:Contemporary blues musicians]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Minneapolis]]