ps====\nMG [[Wesley Merritt]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:25%;\"|Division\n! style=\"width:25%;\"|Brigade\n! Regiments and others\n|-\n| rowspan=4 |\nFirst Division\n\n<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nBG [[Thomas Devin|Thomas C. Devin]]\n| [[Michigan Brigade|1st Brigade]]\n<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol Peter Stagg\n|\n* [[1st Michigan Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|1st Michigan Cavalry]]: Ltc George R. Maxwell ('''w''', April 1), Cpt Edward L. Negus\n* [[5th Michigan Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|5th Michigan Cavalry]]: Ltc [[Smith H. Hastings]]\n* [[6th Michigan Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|6th Michigan Cavalry]]: Ltc Harvey H. Vinton\n* [[7th Michigan Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|7th Michigan Cavalry]]: Ltc George G. Briggs\n|-\n| 2nd Brigade\n<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol [[Charles L. Fitzhugh]]\n|\n* 6th New York Cavalry: Maj Harrison White\n* [[9th Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry|9th New York Cavalry]]: Maj James R. Dinnin\n* [[19th Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry|19th New York Cavalry (1st Dragoons)]]: Maj Howard M. Smith\n* [[17th Pennsylvania Cavalry]]: Ltc Coe Durland\n*[[20th Pennsylvania Cavalry]]: Ltc Gabriel Middleton\n|-\n| 3rd (Reserve) Brigade\n<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;\nBG [[Alfred Gibbs]]\n|\n* [[2nd Regiment of Cavalry, Massachusetts Volunteers|2nd Massachusetts Cavalry]]: Col [[Caspar Crowninshield]]\n* [[6th Pennsylvania Cavalry]] (6 companies): Col Charles L. Leiper\n* [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st U.S. Cavalry]]: Cpt Richard S. C. Lord\n* [[5th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|5th U.S. Cavalry]]: Cpt Thomas Drummond ('''k''', April 1), Lt Gustavus Urban\n* [[6th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|6th U.S. Cavalry]]: Maj Robert M. Morris\n|-\n| Artillery\n|\n* [[4th U.S. Light Artillery, Battery C|4th U.S. Artillery, Battery C]] & Battery E: Cpt Marcus P. Miller\n|-\n| rowspan=3 |\nThird Division\n\n<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nBvt MG [[George Armstrong Custer|George A. Custer]]\n| 1st Brigade\n<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol [[Alexander Cummings McWhorter Pennington, Jr.|Alexander C. M. Pennington Jr.]]\n|\n* [[1st Connecticut Cavalry Regiment|1st Connecticut Cavalry]]: Col [[Brayton Ives]]\n* [[3rd New Jersey Volunteer Cavalry|3rd New Jersey Cavalry]]: Ltc William P. Robeson, Jr. ('''w''', April 1)\n* [[2nd New York Cavalry Regiment|2nd New York Cavalry]]: Col [[Alanson M. Randol]]\n* [[2nd Ohio Cavalry]]: Cpt Albert Barnitz\n|-\n| 2nd Brigade\n<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol [[William Wells (general)|William Wells]]\n|\n* [[8th Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry|8th New York Cavalry]]: Maj James Bliss\n* 15th New York Cavalry: Col John J. Coppinger\n* [[1st Vermont Cavalry]]: Ltc Josiah Hall\n|-\n| 3rd Brigade\n<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;\nCol [[Henry Capehart]]\n|\n* [[1st Regiment New York Volunteer Cavalry|1st New York Cavalry (Lincoln)]]: Ltc Jenyns C. Battersby\n* [[1st West Virginia Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|1st West Virginia Cavalry]]: Maj Shesh B. Howe ('''k''', April 8), Ltc [[Charles E. Capehart]]\n* [[2nd West Virginia Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|2nd West Virginia Cavalry]] (7 companies): Ltc James Allen\n* [[3rd West Virginia Volunteer Cavalry Regiment|3rd West Virginia Cavalry]]: Maj [[John Witcher|John S. Witcher]]\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==References==\n*U.S. War Department, [http://cdl.library.cornell.edu/moa/browse.monographs/waro.html ''The War of the Rebellion'']: ''a Compilation of the [[Official Records of the American Civil War|Official Records]] of the Union and Confederate Armies'', U.S. Government Printing Office, 1880&ndash;1901.\n*[http://www.nps.gov/apco/order-of-battle-appomattox-court-house.htm National Park Service: Appomattox Court House (Union order of battle).]\n* Calkins, Chris. ''The Appomattox Campaign: March 29 &ndash; April 9, 1865''. Conshohocken, Pennsylvania: Combined Books, 1997. {{ISBN|0-938289-54-3}}.\n\n[[Category:American Civil War orders of battle]]\n[[Category:Appomattox Campaign|Union order of battle]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eXXV Corps", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appomattox_campaign_Union_order_of_battle"}
{"title_page": "Abe Goldberg", "text_new": "{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Abraham''' \"'''Abe'''\" '''Goldberg''' (23 June 1929 \u2013 24 July 2016)<!-- D.O.B. back-calculated from 60th birthday in Sep 1989 --> was a Polish-born Jewish Australian businessman whose Linter Group of companies grew to be a major textile and clothing manufacturing group in the 1980s, before collapsing under a mountain of debt.\n\nGoldberg's family had been in the textiles business in [[Garwolin]] in Poland and, being Jewish, when the Germans invaded in [[World War II]] they were sent to a [[ghetto]], but escaped by paying a farmer to hide them in a cowshed for a year and a half. After the war in 1948 they emigrated to [[Australia]] and set up in business in [[Melbourne]].\n\nGoldberg found the [[ANZ Bank]] a ready lender in those days. The bank had quite deliberately cultivated Melbourne's Jewish community, believing them to be hard working and good credit risks. So with finance Goldberg got started in the 1970s doing mergers and deals in the textile business.\n\nGoldberg floated his Linter Group on the [[Australian Stock Exchange]] in March 1985, helped by a loose group of men known as the AFP boys (for their associations with the [[Australian Farming Property]] company). During the next two years Linter continually changed shape and variously owned or controlled many famous Australian brands like [[King Gee]], [[Speedo]]s, [[Stubbies (brand)|Stubbies]] and [[Pelaco]].\n\nThe stock market crash of 1987 hit the deal-making hard, but over the next few years in fact allowed Goldberg to take most of his empire private, funded by debt. His bankers were still quite happy on his 60th birthday in September 1989, but when rumours started doing the rounds later that year they appointed Lindsay Maxsted of KPMG to look over the books.\n\nWhat Maxsted found in early 1990 was an enormously complex web of inter-company relationships, and total liabilities of some $1700m, which was far more than anyone knew and which exceeded estimated assets by at least $425m. Maxsted thought Goldberg had probably been technically insolvent ever since the stock market crash of 1987. The assets in liquidation didn't realize their initial estimates and the shortfall blew out to $750m.\n\nThe lenders for years had concentrated on Linter's excellent brands instead of the company's debt servicing ability. The group was probably only ever making perhaps $60m or $70m before tax, and (even with asset price inflation helping) that could never support loans of $1700m at prevailing interest rates (of up to 20%). Credit rating services like [[Moody's]] had Linter at [[junk bond]] status as early as 1988, but even that hadn't mattered.\n\nGoldberg had made various personal guarantees for the group and was consequently bankrupted, but not before he'd fled to Europe, where he settled back in his native Poland in 1992. Poland had no extradition treaty with Australia at that time so warrants issued in Australia for his arrest could not be executed. [[The Bulletin (Australian periodical)|The Bulletin]] magazine found him in [[Warsaw]] in 2005, apparently back in business as a property tycoon, and with little inclination to return to Australia.  Goldberg died in July 2016 of natural causes in [[Poland]].<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2005/11/08/1131407638770.html?oneclick=true Missing magnate surfaces as a Polish property tycoon], [[Sydney Morning Herald]], 9 November 2005</ref><ref>[http://www.ericellis.com/abe.htm The one that got away] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703172928/http://www.ericellis.com/abe.htm |date=3 July 2008 }}</ref><ref>http://www.polin.pl/en/news/2016/07/26/farewell-to-aleksander-goldberg</ref>\n\n== References ==\n* [[Trevor Sykes]], ''The Bold Riders'', second edition, 1996, {{ISBN|1-86448-184-6}}.\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldberg, Abe}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Polish Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n'''Abraham''' \"'''Abe'''\" '''Goldberg''' (23 June 1929 \u2013 24 July 2016)<!-- D.O.B. back-calculated from 60th birthday in Sep 1989 --> was a Polish-born Jewish Australian businessman whose Linter Group of companies grew to be a major textile and clothing manufacturing group in the 1980s, before collapsing under a mountain of debt.\n\nGoldberg's family had been in the textiles business in [[Garwolin]] in Poland and, being Jewish, when the Germans invaded in [[World War II]] they were sent to a [[ghetto]], but escaped by paying a farmer to hide them in a cowshed for a year and a half. After the war in 1948 they emigrated to [[Australia]] and set up in business in [[Melbourne]].\n\nGoldberg found the [[ANZ Bank]] a ready lender in those days. The bank had quite deliberately cultivated Melbourne's Jewish community, believing them to be hard working and good credit risks. So with finance Goldberg got started in the 1970s doing mergers and deals in the textile business.\n\nGoldberg floated his Linter Group on the [[Australian Stock Exchange]] in March 1985, helped by a loose group of men known as the AFP boys (for their associations with the [[Australian Farming Property]] company). During the next two years Linter continually changed shape and variously owned or controlled many famous Australian brands like [[King Gee]], [[Speedo]]s, [[Stubbies (brand)|Stubbies]] and [[Pelaco]].\n\nThe stock market crash of 1987 hit the deal-making hard, but over the next few years in fact allowed Goldberg to take most of his empire private, funded by debt. His bankers were still quite happy on his 60th birthday in September 1989, but when rumours started doing the rounds later that year they appointed Lindsay Maxsted of KPMG to look over the books.\n\nWhat Maxsted found in early 1990 was an enormously complex web of inter-company relationships, and total liabilities of some $1700m, which was far more than anyone knew and which exceeded estimated assets by at least $425m. Maxsted thought Goldberg had probably been technically insolvent ever since the stock market crash of 1987. The assets in liquidation didn't realize their initial estimates and the shortfall blew out to $750m.\n\nThe lenders for years had concentrated on Linter's excellent brands instead of the company's debt servicing ability. The group was probably only ever making perhaps $60m or $70m before tax, and (even with asset price inflation helping) that could never support loans of $1700m at prevailing interest rates (of up to 20%). Credit rating services like [[Moody's]] had Linter at [[junk bond]] status as early as 1988, but even that hadn't mattered.\n\nGoldberg had made various personal guarantees for the group and was consequently bankrupted, but not before he'd fled to Europe, where he settled back in his native Poland in 1992. Poland had no extradition treaty with Australia at that time so warrants issued in Australia for his arrest could not be executed. [[The Bulletin (Australian periodical)|The Bulletin]] magazine found him in [[Warsaw]] in 2005, apparently back in business as a property tycoon, and with little inclination to return to Australia.  Goldberg died in July 2016 of natural causes in [[Poland]].<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2005/11/08/1131407638770.html?oneclick=true Missing magnate surfaces as a Polish property tycoon], [[Sydney Morning Herald]], 9 November 2005</ref><ref>[http://www.ericellis.com/abe.htm The one that got away] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703172928/http://www.ericellis.com/abe.htm |date=3 July 2008 }}</ref><ref>http://www.polin.pl/en/news/2016/07/26/farewell-to-aleksander-goldberg</ref>\n\n== References ==\n* [[Trevor Sykes]], ''The Bold Riders'', second edition, 1996, {{ISBN|1-86448-184-6}}.\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldberg, Abe}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Polish Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian Jews]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Polish emigrants to Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "date format audit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abe_Goldberg"}
{"title_page": "Beer Money", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Beer money (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Beer Money\n| cover      = Kip Moore - Beer Money single cover.jpg\n| alt        = The cover consists of overlaying images of American dollar bills and the tops of beer cans.\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Kip Moore]]\n| album      = [[Up All Night (Kip Moore album)|Up All Night]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2012|7|9}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2012\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=38}}\n| label      = [[Universal Music Group Nashville|MCA Nashville]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Kip Moore|[[Blair Daly]]|[[Troy Verges]]}}\n| producer   = [[Brett James]]\n| prev_title = [[Somethin' 'Bout a Truck]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Hey Pretty Girl]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n}}\"'''Beer Money'''\" is a song recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Kip Moore]]. It was released in July 2012 as his second single from his debut album, ''[[Up All Night (Kip Moore album)|Up All Night]]''. Moore co-wrote the song with [[Blair Daly]] and [[Troy Verges]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Conaway|first=Alanna|title=Kip Moore, 'Beer Money' \u2013 Lyrics Uncovered|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/kip-moore-beer-money-lyrics/|accessdate=September 6, 2012|publisher=Taste of Country|date=July 10, 2012}}</ref> The song received positive reviews from critics who praised Moore's vocals and use of imagery for elevating the ordinary material.\n\n\"Beer Money\" peaked at number three on the ''Billboard'' [[Country Airplay]] chart. It also charted at number seven on the [[Hot Country Songs]] chart and number 51 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]. It was certified [[Gold (music sales)|Gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting sales of over half-a-million units in that country. In Canada, it peaked at number one on the [[Canada Country|Country]] chart and number 58 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]]. The accompanying music video for the song was directed by [[Peter Zavadil]].\n\n==Critical reception==\nBilly Dukes of ''[[Taste of Country]]'' gave the song three and a half stars out of five, writing that \"what takes this song past ordinary is Moore's grave vocals and story-telling ability.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dukes|first=Billy|title=Kip Moore, 'Beer Money' \u2013 Song Review|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/kip-moore-beer-money/|accessdate=September 6, 2012|publisher=Taste of Country|date=June 26, 2012}}</ref> Matt Bjorke of ''Roughstock'' also gave the song a favorable review, calling it \"another strong mood-setting, sing-a-long ready country/rocker.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bjorke|first=Matt|title=The Weekly Single Recap: June 22, 2012|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/the-weekly-single-recap-june-22-2012|accessdate=September 6, 2012|publisher=Roughstock|date=June 22, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626230834/http://www.roughstock.com/blog/the-weekly-single-recap-june-22-2012|archivedate=June 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by [[Peter Zavadil]] and premiered in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/kip-moore/837792/beer-money.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Kip Moore : Beer Money|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> The video starts with Moore playing a mechanic who gets into an argument with his boss (played by Moore's real-life manager Shawn McSpadden).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.countryweekly.com/news/kip-moore-uses-real-life-tension-beer-money-video|title=Kip Moore Uses Real-Life Tension in \"Beer Money\" Video|last=Schmitt|first=Brad|work=[[Nash Country Weekly|Country Weekly]]|publisher=[[American Media (publisher)|American Media, Inc.]]|date=November 29, 2012|accessdate=September 17, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909050551/http://www.countryweekly.com/news/kip-moore-uses-real-life-tension-beer-money-video|archivedate=September 9, 2015}}</ref> It then follows him picking up his girlfriend from a diner and taking her to a late night barn party where he performs. The video also follows a group of men stealing a keg from a beer delivery truck driver and taking it to said party.\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Beer Money\" debuted at number 57 on the U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] chart for the week of July 7, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Morris|first=Edward|title=Kenny Chesney Lands a Big One With ''Welcome to the Fishbowl''|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1688797/kenny-chesney-lands-a-big-one-with-welcome-to-the-fishbowl.jhtml|accessdate=September 6, 2012|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|date=June 30, 2012}}</ref> It also debuted at number 99 on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart for the week of October 6, 2012. It also debuted at number 90 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]] chart for the week of November 24, 2012.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2012\u201313)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|58|artist=Kip Moore|artistid={{BillboardID|Kip Moore}}|song=Beer Money}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadacountry|1|artist=Kip Moore|artistid=1639640}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|51|artist=Kip Moore|artistid=1639640}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|7|artist=Kip Moore|artistid=1639640}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountryairplay|3|artist=Kip Moore|artistid=1639640}}\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2012)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2012/hot-country-songs | title=Best of 2012: Hot Country Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2012 | accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 59\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2013)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| US [[Country Airplay]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.billboard.biz/bbbiz/photos/pdf/2013/country_update_1216.pdf|title=Billboard Country Update for December 16, 2013|page=21|date=December 16, 2013|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=December 17, 2013}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 61\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2013/hot-country-songs | title=Best of 2013: Hot Country Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2013 | accessdate=December 13, 2013}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 63\n|-\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United States|artist=Kip Moore|title=Beer Money|award=Gold|certyear=2013|certmonth=6|relyear=2012|access-date=June 19, 2013}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|kip-moore|beer-money}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Kip Moore}}\n\n[[Category:2012 singles]]\n[[Category:2012 songs]]\n[[Category:Kip Moore songs]]\n[[Category:MCA Nashville Records singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Canada Country number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Peter Zavadil]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Brett James]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Blair Daly]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kip Moore]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Troy Verges]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Beer money (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Beer Money\n| cover      = Kip Moore - Beer Money single cover.jpg\n| alt        = The cover consists of overlaying images of American dollar bills and the tops of beer cans.\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Kip Moore]]\n| album      = [[Up All Night (Kip Moore album)|Up All Night]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2012|7|9}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2012\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=38}}\n| label      = [[Universal Music Group Nashville|MCA Nashville]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Kip Moore|[[Blair Daly]]|[[Troy Verges]]}}\n| producer   = [[Brett James]]\n| prev_title = [[Somethin' 'Bout a Truck]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Hey Pretty Girl]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n}}\"'''Beer Money'''\" is a song recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Kip Moore]]. It was released in July 2012 as his second single from his debut album, ''[[Up All Night (Kip Moore album)|Up All Night]]''. Moore co-wrote the song with [[Blair Daly]] and [[Troy Verges]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Conaway|first=Alanna|title=Kip Moore, 'Beer Money' \u2013 Lyrics Uncovered|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/kip-moore-beer-money-lyrics/|accessdate=September 6, 2012|publisher=Taste of Country|date=July 10, 2012}}</ref> The song received positive reviews from critics who praised Moore's vocals and use of imagery for elevating the ordinary material.\n\n\"Beer Money\" peaked at number 3 on the ''Billboard'' [[Country Airplay]] chart. It also charted at number 7 on the [[Hot Country Songs]] chart and number 51 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]. It was certified [[Gold (music sales)|Gold]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting sales of over half-a-million units in that country. In Canada, it peaked at number one on the [[Canada Country|Country]] chart and number 58 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]]. The accompanying music video for the song was directed by [[Peter Zavadil]].\n\n==Critical reception==\nBilly Dukes of ''[[Taste of Country]]'' gave the song three and a half stars out of five, writing that \"what takes this song past ordinary is Moore's grave vocals and story-telling ability.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dukes|first=Billy|title=Kip Moore, 'Beer Money' \u2013 Song Review|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/kip-moore-beer-money/|accessdate=September 6, 2012|publisher=Taste of Country|date=June 26, 2012}}</ref> Matt Bjorke of ''Roughstock'' also gave the song a favorable review, calling it \"another strong mood-setting, sing-a-long ready country/rocker.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Bjorke|first=Matt|title=The Weekly Single Recap: June 22, 2012|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/the-weekly-single-recap-june-22-2012|accessdate=September 6, 2012|publisher=Roughstock|date=June 22, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120626230834/http://www.roughstock.com/blog/the-weekly-single-recap-june-22-2012|archivedate=June 26, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by [[Peter Zavadil]] and premiered in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/kip-moore/837792/beer-money.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Kip Moore : Beer Money|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> The video starts with Moore playing a mechanic who gets into an argument with his boss (played by Moore's real-life manager Shawn McSpadden).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.countryweekly.com/news/kip-moore-uses-real-life-tension-beer-money-video|title=Kip Moore Uses Real-Life Tension in \"Beer Money\" Video|last=Schmitt|first=Brad|work=[[Nash Country Weekly|Country Weekly]]|publisher=[[American Media (publisher)|American Media, Inc.]]|date=November 29, 2012|accessdate=September 17, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909050551/http://www.countryweekly.com/news/kip-moore-uses-real-life-tension-beer-money-video|archivedate=September 9, 2015}}</ref> It then follows him picking up his girlfriend from a diner and taking her to a late night barn party where he performs. The video also follows a group of men stealing a keg from a beer delivery truck driver and taking it to said party.\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Beer Money\" debuted at number 57 on the U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] chart for the week of July 7, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Morris|first=Edward|title=Kenny Chesney Lands a Big One With ''Welcome to the Fishbowl''|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1688797/kenny-chesney-lands-a-big-one-with-welcome-to-the-fishbowl.jhtml|accessdate=September 6, 2012|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|date=June 30, 2012}}</ref> It also debuted at number 99 on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart for the week of October 6, 2012. It also debuted at number 90 on the [[Canadian Hot 100]] chart for the week of November 24, 2012.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2012\u201313)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|58|artist=Kip Moore|artistid={{BillboardID|Kip Moore}}|song=Beer Money}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadacountry|1|artist=Kip Moore|artistid=1639640}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|51|artist=Kip Moore|artistid=1639640}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|7|artist=Kip Moore|artistid=1639640}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountryairplay|3|artist=Kip Moore|artistid=1639640}}\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2012)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| US [[Hot Country Songs]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2012/hot-country-songs | title=Best of 2012: Hot Country Songs | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | date=2012 | accessdate=December 14, 2012}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\" | 59\n|-\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2013)\n!scope=\"col\"|Position\n|-\n| US [[Country Airplay]] (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.billboard.biz/bbbiz/photos/pdf/2013/country_update_1216.pdf|title