{"title_page": "Canting arms", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n{{Cleanup lang |date=August 2019 }}\n[[File:Arms of Castile and Leon.svg|thumb|A common simple example of canting arms: the ''[[Heraldry of Castile|castle]]'' representing the Kingdom of ''[[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]]'' and the ''[[Heraldry of Le\u00f3n|lion]]'' representing the Kingdom of ''[[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldica.org/topics/canting.htm|title=Tinctures|publisher=}}</ref>]]\n\n'''Canting arms''' are [[heraldry|heraldic]] bearings that represent the bearer's name (or, less often, some attribute or function) in a [[visual pun]] or [[rebus]]. The term was derived from the [[Anglo-Norman language|Anglo-Norman]] ''cant'', meaning song or singing.\n\nFrench heralds used the term ''armes parlantes'' ({{Lang-en|\"talking arms\"}}), as they would sound out the name of the armiger. Many armorial allusions require research for elucidation because of changes in language and dialect that have occurred over the past millennium.\n\nCanting arms \u2013 some in the form of rebuses \u2013 are quite common in German civic heraldry. They have also been increasingly used in the 20th century among the British royal family.{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}} When the visual representation is not straightforward but as complex as a [[rebus]], this is sometimes called a ''rebus coat of arms''.{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\nAn [[in-joke]] among the [[Society for Creative Anachronism]] heralds is the [[pun]], \"Heralds don't pun; they cant.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Neznanich, Modar|title=Heraldry for Those Who Cant|url=http://www.modaruniversity.org/Heraldry-for-Those-Who-Cant.pdf|accessdate=2 July 2012}} Cites 72 historical examples of canting arms, as well as SCA usage.</ref>\n\n== Examples of canting arms ==\n\n=== Personal coat of arms ===\nA famous example of canting arms are those of [[Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother]] (consort of King [[George VI]] of the United Kingdom). Her arms (pictured below) contain in sinister (i.e. on the bearer's left, viewer's right) the bows and blue lions that make up the arms of the Bowes and Lyon families.\n\n<gallery perrow=\"6\">\nFile:Arms of Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon.svg|[[Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon]]: [[bow (weapon)|bows]] and [[lion]]s\nFile:Arms of Beatrice of York.svg|[[Princess Beatrice of York]]: ''Beatrice'' = bee thrice = three [[bee]]s\nFile:Rosetti family coat of arms (common large version).svg|[[Rosetti family]]: three [[rose (heraldry)|roses]]\nFile:Quintin Hogg Arms.svg|[[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone]]: three [[Pig|hog]]'s heads\nFile:Cokborgne blason.png|[[Cockburn (surname)|Cockburn]]: three [[Rooster|cocks]]\nFile:Crowninsshield Coat of Arms.jpg|[[Crowninshield family]]: [[crown (headgear)|crown]] on the [[shield]]\nFile:Blason Avrecourt.svg|[[De Barry family]]: three [[Bar (heraldry)|bars]] gemelles\nFile:Costa.png|Coat of arms of the head of the Portuguese [[Costa (surname)|Costa family]]: ''costa'' means \"rib\" in [[Latin]]\nFile:Coat of Arms of Dwight Eisenhower.svg|[[Dwight D. Eisenhower|President Eisenhower]]: a blacksmith's [[anvil]], as ''Eisenhauer'' = [[German language|German]] for \"iron-hewer\"\nFile:Flag of Maryland.svg|[[Flag of Maryland]], originally the arms of [[George Calvert, 1st Lord Baltimore]], whose mother's maiden name was Crossland; the latter's arms shows a [[cross]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Flags|author=Englefield, Eric|date=1979|publisher=Ward Lock|page=104}}</ref>\nFile:Coat of Arms of Theodore Roosevelt.svg|[[Theodore Roosevelt]]: roses-[[veldt|fields]]\nFile:Blason de la famille Van Dievoet (Bruxelles).svg|[[Van Dievoet family]]: ''Voet'' means \"foot\" in [[Dutch language|Dutch]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/fr/dictionnaire/neerlandais-anglais/voet|title=voet {{!}} traduction du n\u00e9erlandais vers l'anglais - Cambridge Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|language=fr|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>  \n</gallery>\n\n=== Municipal coat of arms ===\nMunicipal coats of arms which interpret the town's name in rebus form are also called canting. Here are a few examples.\n<gallery>\nFile:Bras\u00e3o de Berwickshire.png|The arms of [[Berwickshire]], Scotland: [[Bear]] and [[Wych Elm]]\nFile:Elmbridge BC Crest of Arms.png|[[Borough of Elmbridge|Elmbridge]], [[Surrey]] (1974): [[Ulmus|elm]] tree on bridge. (The toponym is related to bridges but not to elms; the prefix refers to ''Emel'', a former name for the [[river Mole]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Room, Adrian|title=Dictionary Of Place Names In The British Isles|url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofplac0000room|url-access=registration|publisher=Bloomsbury|year=1988|page=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofplac0000room/page/128 128]}}</ref>)\nFile:Blason de la ville de Ch\u00e2teaurenard (13).svg|[[Ch\u00e2teaurenard]]: ''Ch\u00e2teau'' = castle; ''Renard'' = fox\nFile:DEU Eberbach COA.svg|[[Eberbach (Baden)|Eberbach]] (1976): ''Eber'' = boar; ''Bach'' = brook (wavy blue fess)\nFile:Hensbroek.svg|of the village of [[Hensbroek]] in North Holland interprets the toponym as \"hen-breeches\" (the toponym is unrelated to either \"hen\" or \"breeches\", deriving from a personal name ''Hein'' and the Dutch cognate of \"brook\", i.e. \"Henry's brook\".)\nFile:FEC.png|[[Freixo de Espada \u00e0 Cinta]] (1926): ''Freixo'' = [[Fraxinus|ash]]; ''de Espada'' = with [[sword]]; ''\u00e0 Cinta'' = at the waist, in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]\nFile:Falkenberg kommunvapen - Riksarkivet Sverige.png|[[Falkenberg Municipality|Falkenberg]] (1948): ''Falken'' = falcon; ''Berg'' = hill, in [[Swedish language|Swedish]]\nFile:Sein\u00e4joki.vaakuna.svg|[[Sein\u00e4joki]] (1951): ''sein\u00e4'' = wall, ''joki'' = river, in [[Finnish language|Finnish]]\nFile:Coat of arms of Berlin.svg|[[Berlin]] (1954): ''B\u00e4r'' = bear\nFile:Escudo de Manacor (Islas Baleares).svg|[[Manacor]]: ''man'' = hand, ''a'' = at, ''cor'' = heart, in [[Catalan language|Catalan]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Schneider|first=Klaus-Michael|url=http://www.crwflags.com/fotw/flags/es-pm-mc.html|title=Municipality of Manacor|work=Flags of the World|publisher=CRW Flags|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>\nFile:Escut de Torrevella (2001).svg|[[Torrevieja]] (1829): ''Torre'' = tower, ''vieja'' = old\nFile:Coat of Arms of Kryvyi Rih.svg|[[Kryvyi Rih]]: ''Kryvyi'' = crooked, ''Rih'' = horn, in [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]\nFile:Coat of Arms of Rueda (Valladolid).svg|[[Rueda, Valladolid|Rueda]] (1986): ''rueda'' = wheel in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\nFile:POL \u0141\u00f3d\u017a COA.svg|[[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]: \u0141\u00f3d\u017a = boat\nFile:DEU Wolfsburg COA.svg|[[Wolfsburg]]: Wolf's Castle\nFile:Blason ville fr Magenta (Marne).svg|Arms of [[Magenta, Marne|Magenta, France]], feature a [[bend (heraldry)|bend]] [[Dexter and sinister|sinister]] in [[magenta]], an extremely rare [[tincture (heraldry)|tincture]] in heraldry\nFile:\u00d6rnsk\u00f6ldsvik vapen.svg|[[\u00d6rnsk\u00f6ldsvik Municipality|\u00d6rnsk\u00f6ldsvik]] (1894): ''\u00d6rn'' = Eagle, ''Sk\u00f6ld'' = Shield and ''Vik'' = Bay.\nFile:Wappen Fuessen.svg|[[F\u00fcssen]]: F\u00fcssen = feet\n</gallery>\n\n=== Ecclesiastical coats of arms ===\n<gallery>\nFile:CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Lansing.svg|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Lansing]]: The lances crossed per saltire are a play on the name of the see, the city of [[Lansing, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bishop Boyea arms|url=https://www.dioceseoflansing.org/office-bishop/bishop-boyea-coat-arms|website=Diocese of Lansing|publisher=Roman Catholic Diocese of Lansing|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\nFile:CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Rockville Centre.svg|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Rockville Centre]]: The mounds in the circle at the center of the arms are a play on the name of city in which the diocese is based, [[Rockville Centre, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bishop Barres arms|url=https://www.drvc.org/bishops-history/bishop-barres-coat-of-arms-of-his-excellency.html|website=Diocese of Rockville Centre|publisher=Roman Catholic Diocese of Rockville Centre|accessdate=26 July 2018}}</ref>\nFile:Coat of Arms Diocese of Baton Rouge, LA.svg|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Baton Rouge]]: The shield features a red baton, referencing the city name, [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], and its literal French meaning.\nFile:Coat of Arms Diocese of Buffalo, NY.png|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Buffalo]]: The arms feature an [[American bison]], colloquially called a buffalo, carrying a banner of the Cross of St. George (analogous to the heraldic [[Lamb of God]]), referencing the name of city in which the see is based, [[Buffalo, New York]].\nFile:Coat of Arms Diocese of Brownsville, TX.png|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Brownsville]]: The tincture of the field, [[tenn\u00e9]], is depicted as brown, referencing the seat of the diocese, [[Brownsville, Texas]].\nFile:CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix.svg|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix]]: The arms feature a [[phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]], the namesake of the diocesan seat, [[Phoenix, Arizona]].\nFile:Coat of Arms Diocese of Fort Worth, TX.png|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Fort Worth]]: The arms feature a castle, referencing the fort for which the city, [[Fort Worth, Texas]], was named.\nFile:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Anchorage.svg|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Anchorage]]: The anchor references the namesake of the see, [[Anchorage, Alaska]].\nFile:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Hartford.svg|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Hartford]]: The arms feature a [[hart (deer)|hart]], a male deer, in the midst of flowing water, i.e., [[Ford (crossing)|fording]] a body of water, referencing the name of the see, [[Hartford, Connecticut]].\nFile:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles.svg|The arms of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Los Angeles]]: The arms feature three pairs of wings, denoting three angels, and referencing the namesake of the see, [[Los Angeles, California]], which translates to \"the angels.\"\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Canting arms}}\n\n==References==\n* {{Cite web\n|url=http://www.heraldica.org/topics/meaning.htm\n|title=Meaning of Arms\n|work=Heraldica.org\n|date=2001-06-20}}\n\n{{heraldry}}\n\n[[Category:Heraldry]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=August 2011}}\n{{Cleanup lang |date=August 2019 }}\n[[File:Arms of Castile and Leon.svg|thumb|A common simple example of canting arms: the ''[[Heraldry of Castile|castle]]'' representing the Kingdom of ''[[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]]'' and the ''[[Heraldry of Le\u00f3n|lion]]'' representing the Kingdom of ''[[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldica.org/topics/canting.htm|title=Tinctures|publisher=}}</ref>]]\n\n'''Canting arms''' are [[heraldry|heraldic]] bearings that represent the bearer's name (or, less often, some attribute or function) in a [[visual pun]] or [[rebus]]. The term was derived from the [[Anglo-Norman language|Anglo-Norman]] ''cant'', meaning song or singing.\n\nFrench heralds used the term ''armes parlantes'' ({{Lang-en|\"talking arms\"}}), as they would sound out the name of the armiger. Many armorial allusions require research for elucidation because of changes in language and dialect that have occurred over the past millennium.\n\nCanting arms \u2013 some in the form of rebuses \u2013 are quite common in German civic heraldry. They have also been increasingly used in the 20th century among the British royal family.{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}} When the visual representation is not straightforward but as complex as a [[rebus]], this is sometimes called a ''rebus coat of arms''.{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\nAn [[in-joke]] among the [[Society for Creative Anachronism]] heralds is the [[pun]], \"Heralds don't pun; they cant.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Neznanich, Modar|title=Heraldry for Those Who Cant|url=http://www.modaruniversity.org/Heraldry-for-Those-Who-Cant.pdf|accessdate=2 July 2012}} Cites 72 historical examples of canting arms, as well as SCA usage.</ref>\n\n== Examples of canting arms ==\n\n=== Personal coat of arms ===\nA famous example of canting arms are those of [[Queen Elizabeth the Queen Mother]] (consort of King [[George VI]] of the United Kingdom). Her arms (pictured below) contain in sinister (i.e. on the bearer's left, viewer's right) the bows and blue lions that make up the arms of the Bowes and Lyon families.\n\n<gallery perrow=\"6\">\nFile:Arms of Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon.svg|[[Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon]]: [[bow (weapon)|bows]] and [[lion]]s\nFile:Arms of Beatrice of York.svg|[[Princess Beatrice of York]]: ''Beatrice'' = bee thrice = three [[bee]]s\nFile:Rosetti family coat of arms (common large version).svg|[[Rosetti family]]: three [[rose (heraldry)|roses]]\nFile:Quintin Hogg Arms.svg|[[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone]]: three [[Pig|hog]]'s heads\nFile:Cokborgne blason.png|[[Cockburn (surname)|Cockburn]]: three [[Rooster|cocks]]\nFile:Crowninsshield Coat of Arms.jpg|[[Crowninshield family]]: [[crown (headgear)|crown]] on the [[shield]]\nFile:Blason Avrecourt.svg|[[De Barry family]]: three [[Bar (heraldry)|bars]] gemelles\nFile:Costa.png|Coat of arms of the head of the Portuguese [[Costa (surname)|Costa family]]: ''costa'' means \"rib\" in [[Latin]]\nFile:Coat of Arms of Dwight Eisenhower.svg|[[Dwight D. Eisenhower|President Eisenhower]]: a blacksmith's [[anvil]], as ''Eisenhauer'' = [[German language|German]] for \"iron-hewer\"\nFile:Flag of Maryland.svg|[[Flag of Maryland]], originally the arms of [[George Calvert, 1st Lord Baltimore]], whose mother's maiden name was Crossland; the latter's arms shows a [[cross]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Flags|author=Englefield, Eric|date=1979|publisher=Ward Lock|page=104}}</ref>\nFile:Coat of Arms of Theodore Roosevelt.svg|[[Theodore Roosevelt]]: roses-[[veldt|fields]]\nFile:Blason de la famille Van Dievoet (Bruxelles).svg|[[Van Dievoet family]]: ''Voet'' means 'foot' in [[Dutch language|Dutch]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/fr/dictionnaire/neerlandais-anglais/voet|title=voet {{!}} traduction du n\u00e9erlandais vers l'anglais - Cambridge Dictionary|website=dictionary.cambridge.org|language=fr|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref> \n</gallery>\n\n=== Municipal coat of arms ===\nMunicipal coats of arms which interpret the town's name in rebus form are also called canting. Here are a few examples.\n<gallery>\nFile:Bras\u00e3o de Berwickshire.png|The arms of [[Berwickshire]], Scotland: [[Bear]] and [[Wych Elm]]\nFile:Elmbridge BC Crest of Arms.png|[[Borough of Elmbridge|Elmbridge]], [[Surrey]] (1974): [[Ulmus|elm]] tree on bridge. (The toponym is related to bridges but not to elms; the prefix refers to ''Emel'', a former name for the [[river Mole]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Room, Adrian|title=Dictionary Of Place Names In The British Isles|url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofplac0000room|url-access=registration|publisher=Bloomsbury|year=1988|page=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofplac0000room/page/128 128]}}</ref>)\nFile:Blason de la ville de Ch\u00e2teaurenard (13).svg|[[Ch\u00e2teaurenard]]: ''Ch\u00e2teau'' = castle; ''Renard'' = fox\nFile:DEU Eberbach COA.svg|[[Eberbach (Baden)|Eberbach]] (1976): ''Eber'' = boar; ''Bach'' = brook (wavy blue fess)\nFile:Hensbroek.svg|of the village of [[Hensbroek]] in North Holland interprets the toponym as \"hen-breeches\" (the toponym is unrelated to either \"hen\" or \"breeches\", deriving from a personal name ''Hein'' and the Dutch cognate of \"brook\", i.e. \"Henry's brook\".)\nFile:FEC.png|[[Freixo de Espada \u00e0 Cinta]] (1926): ''Freixo'' = [[Fraxinus|ash]]; ''de Espada'' = with [[sword]]; ''\u00e0 Cinta'' = at the waist, in [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]\nFile:Falkenberg kommunvapen - Riksarkiv